<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="51092">Diagnosis</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="51092">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Mulsant" authorityYear="1850" class="Insecta" family="Coccinellidae" genus="Brumus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Brumus" order="Coleoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="51092" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="51092">Brumus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
can be distinguished from other genera of the tribe 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Mulsant" authorityYear="1846" lsidName="" pageId="0" pageNumber="51092" rank="tribe" tribe="Chilocorini">Chilocorini</taxonomicName>
by the following combination of characters: antenna 10-segmented, terminal antennomere very small and embedded in penultimate segment; pronotal basal margin entirely bordered with submarginal line; elytral epipleura narrow, more or less horizontal and without foveae; abdominal postcoxal lines complete; mid and hind tibiae with two apical spurs; tarsal claws without basal tooth, only slightly swollen at base.
</paragraph>
